@vercasso Hi... :) I spent two days looking at your logic and I couldn't figure why you used two counter variables. But I know the issue is with the counters... Also, there is a better tool to extract groups of "size" from an array, the Slice() method. Which is not in the Hints but it was previously introduced in "Bonfire: Truncate a string".
Another issue... your If statement seems to have the logic reversed, I think you should have most of your calculations as part of the first half of the block code, and the exceptions in the Else statement. Not sure if this makes sense, but I thought the if statement was overly complicated. I used a While instead and I think it makes it easier to read and to follow.
```

function chunk(arr, size) {
  var tempArray = [];
  var finalArray= [];
  var j = 0;
  // looping through arr
  for (i=0;i<arr.length;i++)
  {
    // if I reach the maximum size
    if(j===size)
    {
      finalArray.push(tempArray);
      j=0;
      i--;
    }else{
      tempArray[j]=arr[i];
      j++;
    }
  }
// final push of temp into final Array
    finalArray.push(tempArray); 
  return finalArray;
}

chunk(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd'], 2);
